<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="content-audit-basics">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>ux-researcher</domain>
    <summary>Systematic inventory and quality review of site content: catalog, evaluate against rubric criteria, and produce keep/update/consolidate/remove actions.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>content</tag>
      <tag>audit</tag>
      <tag>inventory</tag>
      <tag>quality</tag>
      <tag>scoring</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>audit</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Content Audit Basics</title>
    <summary>A content audit is a systematic inventory and quality review of all content on a site or application. It catalogs what exists (URL, type, owner, date, analytics), evaluates each item against rubric criteria (accuracy, relevance, quality scored 1-5), and produces a keep/update/consolidate/remove action column. The basics methodology covers audit types, spreadsheet schema, evaluation criteria, and tooling.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Without an inventory you cannot make scope decisions for redesigns, migrations, or SEO resets. Subjective &quot;we should clean up the blog&quot; discussions block action; a scored spreadsheet with analytics-joined data unblocks it. LLM-assisted scoring makes audits tractable at scale, but requires a locked rubric, deterministic model settings, and human sign-off on high-traffic rows.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-redesign or migration: build a complete URL inventory with quality scores before scope decisions.</item>
        <item>SEO/content strategy reset: combine crawl data + analytics + LLM quality scoring.</item>
        <item>Quarterly content governance: rolling audits of high-traffic clusters with freshness checks.</item>
        <item>Site consolidation (M&amp;A, multi-brand merge): de-duplicate near-identical pages across domains.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Site under ~50 pages — a manual spreadsheet review is faster than tooling setup.</item>
        <item>Greenfield (content does not yet exist) — use content modeling, not auditing.</item>
        <item>Analytics performance only — GA4/GSC views suffice; no inventory needed.</item>
        <item>Pre-launch QA of a single page batch — use editorial review instead.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="audit-types">
      <p>Choose audit type based on the decision being made: quantitative (inventory — what exists) when scope is unknown; qualitative (quality evaluation) when decisions require quality scoring; comparative (consistency check) when merging or migrating; ROI-focused (analytics-driven) when prioritizing update investment.</p>
      <p>Quantitative: count and categorize. Qualitative: assess against rubric criteria (accuracy, relevance, quality). Comparative: check consistency across content. ROI-focused: analytics-driven — traffic, engagement, conversions per URL.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Choose audit type based on the decision being made: quantitative (inventory — what exists) when scope is unknown; qualitative (quality evaluation) when decisions require quality scoring; comparative (consistency check) when merging or migrating; ROI-focused (analytics-driven) when prioritizing update investment.</statement>
        <rationale>Using a qualitative audit when an inventory suffices wastes effort. Using an inventory-only audit when quality decisions are needed leaves the hardest question unanswered.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="when-to-run-each-type">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run a full audit (quantitative + qualitative) before any website redesign, content strategy development, or site consolidation. Run rolling quantitative audits for SEO governance. Skip audit entirely for greenfield (no content yet) and for sites under ~50 pages.</statement>
        <rationale>Sites under 50 pages are faster to review manually than to set up crawl tooling. Greenfield needs content modeling, not auditing.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="audit-frequency">
      <p>Treat content governance as ongoing, not a one-time event. Establish quality standards, review processes, update schedules, ownership, and archival policies after the first audit.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Core pages: quarterly</item>
        <item>Blog/news: bi-annually</item>
        <item>Help/support: quarterly</item>
        <item>Product pages: after major releases</item>
        <item>Legal/policy: annually</item>
      </list>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Treat content governance as ongoing, not a one-time event. Establish quality standards, review processes, update schedules, ownership, and archival policies after the first audit.</statement>
        <rationale>One-time audits decay immediately without governance. Content reverts to its pre-audit state within 6-12 months without structured ownership and review triggers.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="scoring-dimensions">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Score every URL on three dimensions: accuracy (1-5: is the content correct?), relevance (1-5: do users need this?), and quality (1-5: is the writing clear and complete?). Average the three scores to produce an overall score driving the action column.</statement>
        <rationale>Single-dimension scoring (quality only, or traffic only) misses critical cases: high-traffic but inaccurate content causes brand damage; accurate but unreachable content is wasted investment.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Action matrix: 4.0+ → keep as is; 3.0-3.9 → update/improve; 2.0-2.9 → rewrite or consolidate; below 2.0 → remove or archive.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Treat &quot;consolidate&quot; as a distinct action from &quot;remove.&quot; Do not collapse low-traffic pages directly to remove when a canonical merge is the better play.</statement>
        <rationale>LLM scoring agents over-classify low-traffic pages as remove. Canonical merging preserves link equity and consolidates thin content without losing it entirely.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="rubric-locking">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Lock the rubric prompt as a versioned YAML file in the repo. Fix temperature=0 and pin the model version for every scoring run. Do not mix scores from different rubric versions or model versions.</statement>
        <rationale>LLM quality scores drift across runs at non-zero temperature. Same page can score 3 vs 4 without a locked rubric. Cross-cycle comparisons require identical scoring conditions.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Sample 5-10% of LLM scores for human review on every run. Track inter-rater agreement (Cohen's kappa target &gt;0.6) before trusting at scale.</statement>
        <rationale>LLMs score coherently but not necessarily correctly for brand voice or strategic relevance. Human spot-checks provide the calibration signal needed to trust the automated column.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="pipeline-architecture">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Join three data sources before scoring: crawl (existence and structure), GSC (search demand), and GA4 (in-product behavior). Auditing crawl-only produces SEO blind spots.</statement>
        <rationale>Crawl-only audits miss search demand. A low-traffic page with high GSC impressions is under-optimized, not low-value. GA4 shows in-product use that GSC cannot capture.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Pre-extract main content (Trafilatura or Readability) and cap input at ~6k characters per URL before LLM scoring. Do not feed raw HTML.</statement>
        <rationale>Full HTML blows context window and introduces navigation, boilerplate, and script noise. Pre-extraction improves scoring accuracy and reduces token cost.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="inventory-mistakes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Incomplete inventory from sitemap-only crawl missing orphan pages, JS-rendered SPAs, PDFs behind auth, and gated content.</description>
        <reason>Sitemap-only crawls miss 15-30% of URLs depending on site quality. Combine sitemap with log-file or GSC impressions inventory to capture orphans. Exclude gated content before LLM ingestion.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Inventory keyed by URL string rather than URL hash, producing double-counting from redirects and trailing-slash variants.</description>
        <reason>Redirects and trailing slashes silently duplicate rows. Hash the canonical URL after redirect resolution and use the hash as the join key.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="scoring-mistakes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Pages scored by LLM whose value is primarily visual (galleries, infographics, video) receive falsely low quality scores.</description>
        <reason>LLMs cannot see images. Flag image-heavy pages with a content-type classifier before scoring and route them to human review instead of automated scoring.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Content less than 90 days old scored as low-traffic and flagged for removal.</description>
        <reason>GA4 data lags new content by weeks to months. Apply a recency guard: exclude any URL with a publish date less than 90 days before the audit date from traffic-based scoring.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="privacy-and-cost">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Gated or PII-containing pages sent to a cloud LLM scoring agent without exclusion.</description>
        <reason>Gated content may contain PII. Add a robots-style allowlist check upstream of the scoring agent. Never ingest content the user has not consented to share with an external model.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Running Opus-tier scoring on all URLs in a large site without tiering.</description>
        <reason>50k URLs at Opus pricing is non-trivial cost. Use Haiku for first-pass triage, escalate only borderline URLs (score 2-4) to a higher-tier model for re-scoring.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Drive the audit as a pipeline: a crawler agent produces the URL inventory, an enrichment agent joins analytics + GSC + Ahrefs/Semrush data, an LLM scoring agent applies the rubric per URL in batches, and a synthesis agent writes the keep/update/remove recommendations. Human sign-off only on the final action column for any URL with &gt;100 monthly sessions. Cache crawl + analytics outputs to a local SQLite or Parquet file so re-scoring iterations don't re-hit APIs.</p>
      <note>Recommended subagents: faion-ux-researcher-agent (owns the rubric, scores Accuracy/Relevance/Quality, drafts the action column); faion-seo-manager (from pro/marketing/seo-manager, joins Ahrefs/GSC traffic and keyword cannibalization signals); faion-content-marketer (writes the rewrite/consolidation briefs for the URLs marked &quot;Update&quot;); faion-data-analyst style subagent (for statistical sampling when audit covers &gt;5k URLs).</note>
    </section>
    <section name="prompt-pattern">
      <note>Use one prompt per URL, batched 50-100 in parallel; never feed the whole inventory in one context.</note>
      <code lang="text">You are auditing a single URL against this rubric:
{rubric_yaml}
Page text: {extracted_markdown}
Page metrics: {gsc_clicks, ga4_sessions, last_modified}
Return JSON: {accuracy:1-5, relevance:1-5, quality:1-5, action:&quot;keep|update|consolidate|remove&quot;, reason:&lt;=2 sentences}.</code>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/audit-spreadsheet-schema.md" purpose="Column definitions for the content audit spreadsheet (ID, URL, metrics, scores, action)."/>
      <template path="templates/rubric.yaml" purpose="Scoring rubric in YAML for LLM prompt injection; version-controlled for reproducibility."/>
      <template path="templates/audit-pipeline.py" purpose="Async Python sketch: crawl → extract → score via Claude API → write scored.jsonl."/>
    </templates>
